Instagram brought us here ğŸ˜‚
I'm an avid Tupac fan, have been since he was originally MC New York, and Yafeu, Malc, etc were Dramacydal, before they got their alias's & became Thug Life, then The Outlawz. To me, Pac was a genius. I will always defend facts, no hearsay.  But, every 1 saying NLE is using "Hit Em Up" , the answer is yes & no. Pac ACTUALLY sampled a song called "Don't look any futher" by Dennis Edwards (1982) as the main melody & also "loosely"wanted to imitate "Get Money" Junior Mafia. A lot of OG hiphop/rap tracks sampled older tracks. We all know diss tracks are meant to pack a lyrical punch, with undertones of facts/roasting & threats. But, i will say, in my personal experience (as I've not seen/heard EVERY diss track ever recorded by every artist) THIS video to accompany KO, is 1 of the only ones I can think of which is clearly influenced by Pac's hit em up. We know Pac had fire lyrics, and meant every word, but the video content/context was satire. The lookalikes, wigs, and more, was an evident comical roasting moment.  TBH, for its day, pure genuis. Video portraying a different narrative to the heartfelt, Pack a punch, intentional diss. Even now, hit em up is loved by younger generations. So, whilst NLE has clearly been influenced by Pac, he hasn't copied anything. It's NLEs lyrics, concept, story, and work that resulted in this. I don't usually like "newer" disses (as opposed to 80/90 Cubes No Vaseline is another classic) but, credit where credits due. I like this. The video has an old school vibe to it too. Also @NLEtheGreat is that a Death Row Chain I noticed on you? I couldn't see properly, as just watching on my phone for quickly for now. If it IS, you got an OG west side chain right there â˜ºâ˜º Keep being you & keep giving us more like this !!! ğŸ”¥

NLE The Great aka NLE Choppa is showing us whatt a  lyrically inclined  diss with intense entertainment looks like. Some artist are laid back and deep( Kendrick). NLE THE Great aka NLE Choppa is intense and entertaining. The message in  the potrayals along with the lyrics are not getting enough attention. Look at the video, listen to the  lyrics. Every unapologetic artist often gets misunderstood or condemned by some for expressing their creative talent in what may be deemed unconventional and/or socially unaccepted.  That doesn't negate the vision, inspiration and creativity. What is seen as a change in personality or persona is often growth mentally as well as physically.  An unbiased look at this video will undoubtedly garner praise and kudos as a fire diss song/video. Not to mention it's critique of mediocre negativity .

I love this conversation. (I'm 35 now) This is where it's important to listen to our  elders. I love the crystallized wisdom part. Yes, you can be young and have it all together, but through time you learn to KEEP IT GOING. Experience over time is what matters. I'll give an example... YOU play ball in your 20s and hurt yourself or break a bone. And you heal from it. That's not going to be the same TYPE OF HEALING YOU WILL GO THROUGH IN YOUR 50S AND 60S. Yet, you still have to find a way to make it through just like you did back in the 20s. That's why it's important to understand, WITH AGE, comes wisdom if you receive it. BECAUSE there is also a thing called A BREAKING POINT. You only can reach that with TIME! It can either be used as a Breakthrough or a breakdown. Either side only gets harder as you age. crystallized...

Let's break down the symbolism: Youngboy is MJ For the longest are body been comparing young boy to Michael Jackson so what does nle Choppa done he decided to dress up like Michael Jackson in the video and dance like him, and stage design because he is considered as modern day Michael Jackson. People been comparing young boy to Tupac so what does nle Choppa do he decided do not just dress up like Tupac again and dresses up Makaveli but rap over a sample that Tupac use back in the day and on top of that what he do he intertwines both Michael Jackson and Tupac of the flow of the song.   YB gets compared to Chris Brown People also compare young boys to Chris Brown, but it's only a small few. So what does Bryson do? He also imitates Chris Brown in the song as well.  Why does nle also do it? Choppa did this because over the years, people say that he is a wannabe young boy or he's a young boy clone.  On top of that, I guess he's also making imagery that young boy is not Tupac young boy is not Michael Jackson. And what does this mean it also means that these two iconic figures are the ones that the youth looked up to positivity.  The hypocrisy of NLE He mentioned that youngboy is destroying the youth with the drugs, lyrics, etcetera, but the thing is Choppa was doing the same thing with Durk, Von, Savage, etc. I understood the message, but at the same time, it makes him look like a hypocrite for doing the same thing. We may not know what happened behind closed doors but based off a interview a while ago after the diss track dead young boy put out "Know Like I Know" NLE basically was saying he wasn't trying to go against youngboy but King Von was like a brother to him so he went with Durk to sum it up. So when he mentioned in the song he wanted peace and youngboy basically rejected it, it was more like in NLE was trying to cool it off, but didnâ€™t.   Is this jealousy? Could this be envy from Choppa on youngboy has always gotten more recognition than him, maybe . Again, we heard several instances where people compare the two, and it's not even close when it comes to numbers and fanbase.  The controversy Choppa dressing/ imitating as Tupac. Back in 2021, he already imitates Tupac, and he has controversy. By doing that, some people praise them. Some people don't.  Video Symbolism  The black and white checkerboard and the black man looked at the Devil he basically saying that YB is the devil and he also is a slave to the system because we see the guy who's playing as YB is a slave and if you really look deeper into his tour name and his album is called Masa it's like a southern twang instead of saying Master its Masa. And guess what, who is the Masters, the industry, and let's not forget young boy for the longest been saying he want his Masters as in owning to his music a master for a master. So the video and his whole album and tour name are ambiguous when it comes to the meaning.

Let's break down the symbolism: Youngboy is MJ For the longest are body been comparing young boy to Michael Jackson so what does nle Choppa done he decided to dress up like Michael Jackson in the video and dance like him, and stage design because he is considered as modern day Michael Jackson. People been comparing young boy to Tupac so what does nle Choppa do he decided do not just dress up like Tupac again and dresses up Makaveli but rap over a sample that Tupac use back in the day and on top of that what he do he intertwines both Michael Jackson and Tupac of the flow of the song.   YB gets compared to Chris Brown People also compare young boys to Chris Brown, but it's only a small few. So what does Bryson do? He also imitates Chris Brown in the song as well.  Why does nle also do it? Choppa did this because over the years, people say that he is a wannabe young boy or he's a young boy clone.  On top of that, I guess he's also making imagery that young boy is not Tupac young boy is not Michael Jackson. And what does this mean it also means that these two iconic figures are the ones that the youth looked up to positivity.  The hypocrisy of NLE He mentioned that youngboy is destroying the youth with the drugs, lyrics, etcetera, but the thing is Choppa was doing the same thing with Durk, Von, Savage, etc. I understood the message, but at the same time, it makes him look like a hypocrite for doing the same thing. We may not know what happened behind closed doors but based off a interview a while ago after the diss track dead young boy put out "Know Like I Know" NLE basically was saying he wasn't trying to go against youngboy but King Von was like a brother to him so he went with Durk to sum it up. So when he mentioned in the song he wanted peace and youngboy basically rejected it, it was more like in NLE was trying to cool it off, but didnâ€™t.   Is this jealousy? Could this be envy from Choppa on youngboy has always gotten more recognition than him, maybe . Again, we heard several instances where people compare the two, and it's not even close when it comes to numbers and fanbase.  The controversy Choppa dressing/ imitating as Tupac. Back in 2021, he already imitates Tupac, and he has controversy. By doing that, some people praise them. Some people don't.  Video Symbolism  The black and white checkerboard and the black man looked at the Devil he basically saying that YB is the devil and he also is a slave to the system because we see the guy who's playing as YB is a slave and if you really look deeper into his tour name and his album is called Masa it's like a southern twang instead of saying Master its Masa. And guess what, who is the Masters, the industry, and let's not forget young boy for the longest been saying he want his Masters as in owning to his music a master for a master. So the video and his whole album and tour name are ambiguous when it comes to the meaning.
